{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":132740,"duration_api_ms":132430,"num_turns":14,"result":"Here's a summary of the findings:\n\n## Root Cause\n\n**File:** `src/requests/sessions.py`, function `SessionRedirectMixin.rebuild_proxies()`, lines 318–319\n\n```python\nif \"Proxy-Authorization\" in headers:\n    del headers[\"Proxy-Authorization\"]   # unconditional removal\n```\n\nThis runs on every redirect. After deletion, the header is only re-added at lines 328–329 if **both** conditions hold:\n1. The scheme is NOT `https`\n2. Credentials are embedded in the proxy URL itself\n\nSince the user's target is `https://example.com`, condition 1 fails and the header is never restored.\n\n## Why This Changed in 2.26+\n\n- **2.26.0 regression** (fixed in 2.27.0): `Proxy-Authorization` was incorrectly stripped from *all* requests sent via `Session.send`, not just redirects.\n- **2.31.0 security hardening**: Intentionally strips the header on HTTPS redirects to prevent proxy credentials from leaking through the CONNECT tunnel to the destination server.\n\n## When the Header Is Preserved vs. Stripped\n\n| Scenario | Outcome |\n|---|---|\n| HTTP target, proxy URL has embedded `user:pass`, redirect occurs | **Preserved** (re-added) |\n| No redirect at all | **Preserved** (rebuild_proxies never called) |\n| HTTPS target, any redirect | **Stripped** (security intentional) |\n| Any target, proxy URL has no credentials | **Stripped** (nothing to re-add) |\n\n## Fix\n\nUse credentials in the proxy URL instead of the header:\n```python\nproxies={\"https\": \"http://user:pass@proxy:8080\"}\n```\n`HTTPAdapter.proxy_headers()` (`adapters.py:592-611`) extracts these and passes them to urllib3's CONNECT tunnel mechanism, which is not subject to the stripping logic.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"d2b1727c-48a7-45e8-9348-85783182e176","total_cost_usd":0.31457104999999996,"usage":{"input_tokens":1025,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19548,"cache_read_input_